<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

 <exercise label="mcqmatrixsize">
  <title>Matrix Size and Vectors</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following correctly describes a column vector?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A column vector is an <m>m \times 1</m> matrix.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. A vector is treated as a column matrix in this section.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>An <m>1 \times m</m> matrix.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No—that is a row vector.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A square matrix with <m>m=n</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No—square matrices are unrelated to the definition of vectors.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>


<exercise label="mcq-matrix-multiplication">
  <title>Matrix Multiplication Rules</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      When is the matrix product <m>A B</m> defined?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          When <m>A</m> is <m>m \times n</m> and <m>B</m> is <m>n \times p</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The number of columns of <m>A</m> must equal the number of
          rows of <m>B</m>. 
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>When both matrices have the same number of rows.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. Matching rows is not the requirement.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Only when both matrices are square.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          No. Matrix multiplication does not require square matrices.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>


<exercise label="mcq-vector-form-system">
  <title>Writing a System in Matrix Form</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose we have the system
      <md>
        <mrow> x_1' \amp = 2x_1 + 3x_2, </mrow> 
        <mrow> x_2' \amp = -x_1 + 4x_2. </mrow>
      </md>
      Which vector‑matrix form is correct?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \vec{x}' =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              2 \amp 3 \\
              -1 \amp 4
            \end{bmatrix}
            \vec{x}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The matrix is constructed from the coefficients of the system
          exactly as described in the section.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \vec{x}' =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              x_1 \amp x_2 \\
              x_1 \amp x_2
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. The matrix should contain constants, not variables.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \vec{x}' =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              2x_1 + 3x_2 \\
              -x_1 + 4x_2
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          This is simply rewriting the system, not expressing it as 
          <m>A \vec{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>
 
<exercise label="mcqtranspose">
  <title>Understanding the Transpose</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>A</m> is a matrix, what is the transpose <m>A^{T}</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The matrix obtained by swapping rows and columns of <m>A</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The transpose flips rows into columns and vice versa.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The matrix formed by multiplying every entry of <m>A</m> by <m>-1</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. That describes scalar multiplication by <m>-1</m>, not transposition.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The matrix you obtain by reversing the order of columns only.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. Transpose reverses rows and columns.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqdeterminantinvertibility">
  <title>Determinant and Invertibility</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For a square matrix <m>A</m>, which statement about its determinant is correct?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>A</m> is invertible exactly when <m>\det(A) \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. A nonzero determinant means the matrix is invertible, which is
          essential when rewriting or solving linear systems using 
          <m>\vec{x}' = A\vec{x}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\det(A)</m> must always be positive for <m>A</m> to be invertible.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          No. A determinant may be negative or positive; only zero prevents invertibility.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>A</m> is invertible when <m>\det(A) = 0</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect. A zero determinant means <m>A</m> is singular and cannot be inverted.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqmatrixinverse">
  <title>Understanding Inverses</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>A</m> is a square matrix and <m>A^{-1}</m> exists.  
      What property does <m>A^{-1}</m> satisfy?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>A A^{-1} = I</m> and <m>A^{-1} A = I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The inverse undoes the effect of <m>A</m>, producing the 
          identity matrix <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>A^{-1}</m> is obtained by transposing <m>A</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          No. The transpose <m>A^{T}</m> is generally unrelated to the inverse.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>A^{-1}</m> exists for every square matrix.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Incorrect. Only matrices with nonzero determinant are invertible.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>


  <!-- Problem 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="matrixcomputation1">
    <!-- <title>Matrix Addition and Scalar Multiplication</title> -->
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let 
        <m>
          A = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \\
            3 \amp 4
          \end{bmatrix},
          B = \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 0 \\
            -1 \amp 5
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </m>
        Compute <m>2A + B</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        First compute <m>2A</m> by multiplying every entry of <m>A</m> by 2:
      </p>
      <me>
        2A = 
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2\cdot 1 \amp 2\cdot 2 \\
          2\cdot 3 \amp 2\cdot 4
        \end{bmatrix}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \amp 4 \\
          6 \amp 8
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Now add <m>B</m> element‑wise:
      </p>

      <me>
        2A + B =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \amp 4 \\
          6 \amp 8
        \end{bmatrix}
        +
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \amp 0 \\
          -1 \amp 5
        \end{bmatrix}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          4 \amp 4 \\
          5 \amp 13
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Matrix addition and scalar multiplication work entry by entry.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- Problem 2 -->
  <exercise xml:id="matrixcomputation2">
    <!-- <title>Transpose of a Matrix</title> -->
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let
        <m>
          C =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
            -3 \amp 0 \amp 5
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </m>
        Compute the transpose <m>C^{T}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        The transpose swaps rows and columns.  
        So the first row of <m>C</m> becomes the first column of <m>C^{T}</m>,
        and the second row becomes the second column.
      </p>

      <me>
        C^{T} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \amp -3 \\
          4 \amp 0 \\
          2 \amp 5
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- Problem 3 -->
  <exercise xml:id="matrixcomputation3">
    <!-- <title>Matrix–Vector Multiplication</title> -->
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let 
        <m>
          A = 
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 3 \\
            -1 \amp 4
          \end{bmatrix},
          \vec{x} =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \\ 2
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </m>
        Compute <m>A \vec{x}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Multiply each row of <m>A</m> by the column vector <m>\vec{x}</m> 
        using dot products, as defined in the section.
      </p>

      <p>
        First row:
        <m>2\cdot 1 + 3\cdot 2 = 2 + 6 = 8</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Second row:
        <m>-1\cdot 1 + 4\cdot 2 = -1 + 8 = 7</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
        A \vec{x} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          8 \\
          7
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        This matches the definition of matrix multiplication using row–column 
        dot products.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


